Arthur <br><br>
In re-reading my previous post, and thinking about atrocities I have a hard time defining it. On one hand war is an atrocity, but I was refering more to conscious killing of innocents as in Mi Lai. This kind of carnage has rarely been perpetrated by people against their own, but most often against those who are different or &quot;outsiders&quot;. <br><br>
Maybe if we looked as all people as one, then we would have much more difficult time engaging in war. (Wouldn't that be nice).<br><br>
I think that I have to agree that ethnography had little to do with how soldiers worked together in Vietnam. I think the primacy of being a cohesive force to save one's arse was the over riding factor. I do think that the dehumanization of the enemy is essential to allow ones psychi to come to terms with prolonged warfare.<br><br>
For me to understand your point about the difference between &quot;Charlie&quot; or the &quot;Gooks&quot; and the Vietnamese people I need to know how you differentiate them and how that differentiation manifested itself in the daily work of war. I rarely hear people making that distinction when people talk about their war experience.<br><br>
Tom I agree that a major factor in the make up of the army was the draft. People of &quot;means&quot; were much more able to avoid the draft, while those without did not have the resources to do so. Another point is that many people of the poorer class (most often but not exclusively non-white) were faced with a choice of being unemployed or under-employed or being employed by the military. GI benefits also offered hope of advancement where little else existed. Those of better means were faced with a choice of a good job after college or fighting a war that put their well-being at risk. <br><br>
Tom and Art.. good points in what you wrote. I am thinking about what you said and may comment again. Thanks
